# Mandatory tests

All production code changes must include appropriate automated tests. Tests should validate expected behavior, edge cases, null handling, error handling, and critical business logic. Production-ready implementations without testing coverage should not be approved.

Apply this rule when:

- implementing new functionality
- modifying business logic
- creating APIs
- modifying data pipelines
- updating distributed systems
- reviewing pull requests
- validating production readiness

## Agent behavior

- For each change set: add or update tests in the same PR unless the user documents an accepted exception (e.g. generated-only paths with an alternative verification plan).
- Prefer fast, deterministic unit tests at boundaries; add integration or pipeline tests when behavior spans services, IO, or Spark/Delta.
- Call out missing coverage explicitly in review instead of treating it as optional.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — New endpoint + core branch logic merged with “tests later” or only manual smoke

✅ GOOD — Same PR includes request/response and auth failure tests, null/validation cases, and at least one regression for the critical branch
```
